Installation
============

Requirements
------------
- Perl 5
- rsync (must be installed on both the backup server and remote hosts)
- SSH access to each remote host (key-based authentication strongly recommended)


1. Install files
----------------
Clone rbackup to your preferred location, e.g. /opt/rbackup:
    cd /opt
    git clone https://github.com/tryggvi/rbackup.git

2. Configure
------------
Copy the config template and edit it:

    cp /opt/rbackup/rbackup.conf.dist /opt/rbackup/rbackup.conf
    Edit /opt/rbackup/rbackup.conf

At minimum set:

    backup_dir   — where backups will be stored, e.g. /data/backup
    logdir       — where log files will be written, e.g. /var/log/rbackup

Then add a [hostname] block for each server you want to back up:

    [web01.example.com]
    user    = root
    include = /etc, /home, /var/www
    exclude = /tmp/

If you need to connect by IP address instead of hostname, add:

    ipaddr = 192.168.1.50


3. Set up SSH key authentication
---------------------------------
rbackup connects to each remote host via SSH. Key-based authentication is required for unattended (cron) use. 

On the backup server:

    ssh-keygen -t ed25519

Copy the public key to each remote host:

    ssh-copy-id root@web01.example.com

Test that passwordless login works before proceeding:
    ssh root@web01.example.com


4. Create required directories
--------------------------------
    mkdir -p /data/backup
    mkdir -p /var/log/rbackup


5. Test
-------
Run a dry run first to verify connectivity and paths without transferring data:

    /opt/rbackup/rbackup.pl -t -v -r

Check the listed hosts and config:

    /opt/rbackup/rbackup.pl -H

Run a real backup:

    /opt/rbackup/rbackup.pl -r -v

Check stats after the first run:

    /opt/rbackup/rbackup.pl -s


6. Schedule with cron
----------------------
Copy the cron file and adjust the path if needed:

    cp rbackup.crond /etc/cron.d/rbackup
    chmod 644 /etc/cron.d/rbackup

The default schedule runs daily at 01:00. Edit /etc/cron.d/rbackup to change the time:

    0 01 * * * root /opt/rbackup/rbackup.pl -r > /dev/null 2>&1
